Applying Markowitz Portfolio Theory

In [13]:
prtf_return =[]
prtf_volatility=[]

for i in range(2000):
    weights = np.random.random(num_assets)
    weights/= np.sum(weights)
    
    prtf_return.append(np.dot(weights, sec_returns.mean()*250))
    prtf_volatility.append(np.sqrt (np.dot(weights.T, np.dot(sec_returns.cov()*250, weights))))

prtf_return= np.array(prtf_return)
prtf_volatility = np.array(prtf_volatility)
prtf_return, prtf_volatility

Getting the best weights for the portfolio

In [16]:
from scipy.optimize import minimize

# Define the constraints
constraints = ({'type': 'eq', 'fun': lambda x: np.sum(x) - 1})

# Define the bounds for each weight
bounds = tuple((0,1) for x in range(num_assets))

# Define the initial guess for the weights
init_guess = num_assets * [1./num_assets]

# Define the function to minimize (negative Sharpe Ratio here)
def min_func(weights):
    return -np.dot(weights, sec_returns.mean()*250) / np.sqrt(np.dot(weights.T, np.dot(sec_returns.cov()*250, weights)))

# Run the optimizer
opt_results = minimize(min_func, init_guess, method='SLSQP', bounds=bounds, constraints=constraints)

# Get the optimal weights
optimal_weights = opt_results.x

optimal_weights
